0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 229 "2.  Polynomials:  Intercepts and Sign.  \+
There are several features about the graphs of polynomials which are i
mportant to track.  These features inform us about the behavior of the
 function.  Those features include the following:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 57 "    a.    x-intercepts of
 the function                   " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 129 "    \+
                   Those values where the graph crosses the x-axis.  T
hose points are solutions of the equation y = f(x) = 0." }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 105 "    b.    regions (intervals) in the domain of the \+
function where the values of the function are positive" }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 215 "                       Those regions where the grap
h lies above the x-axis.  For a continuous function, and in particular
 for polynomials, these regions are bounded by the intercepts and may \+
stretch to +/- infinity." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 105 "    c.    re
gions (intervals) in the domain of the function where the values of th
e function are negative" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 215 "             \+
          Those regions where the graph lies below the x-axis.  For a \+
continuous function, and in particular for polynomials, these regions \+
are bounded by the intercepts and may stretch to +/- infinity." }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 36 "    d.   y-intercept of the function" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 107 "                       The value where t
he graph crosses the y-axis.  The value of the function when x = 0." }
}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 21 "    e.   end limits  " }{TEXT 305 31 "- \+
either up large or down large" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 384 "       \+
                For a polynomial, its values will become either arbitr
arily large in a positive sense or arbitrarily large in a negative sen
se as the domain values tend to infinity.  Graphically, the values on \+
the graph will growth arbitrarily large positively (go up off the grap
h) or arbitrarily large negative (go down off the graph) as the domain
 values tend to infinity.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 87 "          \+
             Similar behavior holds true for approaches to negative in
finity." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
150 "For each of the following polynomials,  provide a graph of the po
lynomial.  Choose a range that will optimally represent the features o
f the graph.   " }{TEXT 268 4 "Also" }{TEXT -1 90 ", for each polynomi
al find each of the above five graphcial characteristics (a.  thru e.)
:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 5 "a.   \+
" }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "y = 6*x^2+24*x-8" "6#/%\"yG,(*&\"\"'\"\"\"*$%\"xG\"
\"#F(F(*&\"#CF(F*F(F(\"\")!\"\"" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 5 "b.   " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "y = 15-9*x-6*x^2;" 
"6#/%\"yG,(\"#:\"\"\"*&\"\"*F'%\"xGF'!\"\"*&\"\"'F'*$F*\"\"#F'F+" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 5 "c.   " }
{XPPEDIT 18 0 "y = x^3-3*x-2;" "6#/%\"yG,(*$%\"xG\"\"$\"\"\"*&F(F)F'F)
!\"\"\"\"#F+" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 4 "d.  " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "y = x^6-6*x^5+16*x^4-48*x^3+80*x^2-96*x+12
8;" "6#/%\"yG,0*$%\"xG\"\"'\"\"\"*&F(F)*$F'\"\"&F)!\"\"*&\"#;F)*$F'\"
\"%F)F)*&\"#[F)*$F'\"\"$F)F-*&\"#!)F)*$F'\"\"#F)F)*&\"#'*F)F'F)F-\"$G
